Security Philosophy: Lab Mapping & The CIA Triad
My security philosophy for this project is built upon the CIA Triad (Center for Internet Security [CIS], 2023), which I have mapped to this specific lab environment:

Confidentiality: Virtualization isolation via UTM keeps the Host and Guest environments separate (Scarfone et al., 2011).

Integrity: The lab_verify.sh script provides a verifiable audit of the workbench standards.

Availability: Demonstrated by the Green Link in Packet Tracer and redundant cloud storage on GitHub.

Security Foundations: Governance & Frameworks
AAA Framework
The AAA Framework manages how I interact with this technical environment:

Authentication: Verifying my identity through my GitHub username and Personal Access Token (PAT).

Authorization: The specific permissions granted to my account to "write" and modify this repository.

Accounting: The use of Git logs to record every update I make, creating a professional audit trail.

Governance in Cybersecurity
Governance represents the rules and oversight that align technical work with business goals. In cybersecurity, governance ensures that technical teams follow established frameworks—such as those provided by NIST—to remain compliant with laws and regulations (Scarfone et al., 2011). It provides the "Security Blueprint" that guides every technical decision I make.

Reflection
Governance is just as important as technical skill because it provides the "why" and "how" for security. While a technical skill allows me to create a repository, governance ensures that the repository is auditable, secure, and compliant with professional standards. Without these frameworks, technical security would be disorganized and difficult to verify. The cybersecurity domain that aligns most with today’s material is GRC (Governance, Risk, and Compliance). This lab specifically highlights the "Compliance" and "Accounting" aspects of maintaining a professional technical workbench.

